\begin_layout Subsection
Time Marching Based on Interpolation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The acquiring of an NIRK method with certain order of accuracy is usually based on a certain integration method and corresponding taylor expansion analysis, as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "kulikov2006familyNIRKOrig"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. However, the present paper proposes a single step method derived with Hermite interpolation (thus called HIRK), which simplifies the acquiring of high stage order and provides an approach to modify the scheme's stability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the first order ODE arising from high-order finite volume method with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu\in \mathbb{R}^N$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}
    \frac{d\uu}{dt} = \R(t, \uu)
\end{equation*}
\end_inset

which is directly taken from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:FVODE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^n$
\end_inset

 as the known numerical solution at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t^n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n+1} = t^{n} + \inc t$
\end_inset

, we first consider the construction of implicit second order time marching methods as an introduction. First, form a linear interpolation for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[t^n, t^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

, which gives an approximate time-distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu(t)=\frac{t^{n+1} - t}{\inc t}\uu^n + \frac{t - t^n}{\inc t}\uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

. Second, use a second order accurate quadrature rule on the linear time distribution. Evidently a trapezoid rule yields trapezoid rule method or Crank-Nicolson method, and midpoint rule yields the second order midpoint method. Inspired by this procedure, now we proceed to construct a high-order version.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a single step implicit method, if the implicitness is already solved, the endpoint values 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^n, \uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 are given. Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^n, \R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 can be directly evaluated, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^n = \R(t^n, \uu^n)$
\end_inset

. Given the endpoint values and corresponding first derivatives, an Hermite interpolation can be given: 
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\ttt}{t^*}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:Hermite}
    \begin{aligned}
        \uu(t) & \approx (1-3{\ttt}^2 - 2 {\ttt}^3)\uu^n
        + (3{\ttt}^2 - 2 {\ttt}^3)\uu^{n+1}                    \\
               & + \inc t ({\ttt} - 2 {\ttt}^2 + {\ttt}^3) \R^n
        + \inc t (- {\ttt}^2 + {\ttt}^3) \R^{n+1}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ttt = (t - t^n)/\inc t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ttt \in [0,1]$
\end_inset

. The Hermite interpolation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Hermite"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\inc t^4)$
\end_inset

 truncation error. Next, a quadrature rule is applied. To utilize the endpoints and reduce memory requirement, we only insert one middle stage at 
\begin_inset Formula $\ttt = c_2$
\end_inset

. Using polynomial interpolation based numerical integration, with nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\ttt = 0,c_2,1$
\end_inset

, the numerical integration of some function 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 would be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:Quad}
    \begin{aligned}
        \int_{t^n}^{t^{n+1}}r(t)dt & \approx \\
         \left(\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{6{c_2}}\right)r(t^n)
         &+
        \left(\frac{1}{6{c_2}(1-{c_2})}\right)r(t^n + c_2\inc t )
        +
        \left(\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{6(1-{c_2})}\right)r(t^{n+1})
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

using the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{t^n}^{t^{n+1}}\R dt = \uu^{n+1} -\uu^{n}$
\end_inset

, there are two algebraic relations and two unknown vectors in total, which is able to form a solvable system. The quadrature rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has truncation error 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\inc t^3)$
\end_inset

 at least, for it is based on second degree polynomial interpolation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summarizing the discussions above, the HIRK method has the form: 
\begin_inset Flex Flex:Subequations
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:HM3"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
        \uu^{n+1} & = \uu^{n} +
        \inc t
        \left[
            b_1\R(t^{n,1}, \uu^n) +
            b_2\R(t^{n,2}, \uu^*) +
            b_3\R(t^{n,3}, \uu^{n+1})
        \right]   \label{eq:HM3-1} \\
        \uu^{*}   & =
        a_1\uu^{n} +
        a_2\uu^{n+1} +
        \inc t
        \left[
            d_1\R(t^{n,1}, \uu^n) +
            d_2\R(t^{n,3}, \uu^{n+1})
            \right] \label{eq:HM3-2}
    \end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n,i}=t^n+c_i\inc t$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_1 = 0, c_3 = 1, c_2\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only stage value besides endpoints is 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

. The internal stage 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 can be explicitly calculated with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which is derived directly from the cubic Hermite interpolation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu$
\end_inset

 on interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[t^n,t^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n,2}$
\end_inset

, which result in the interpolation relation: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        a_2 & = 1 - a_1 = 3{c_2}^2 - 2 {c_2}^3 \\
        d_1 & = {c_2} - 2 {c_2}^2 + {c_2}^3    \\
        d_2 & = - {c_2}^2 + {c_2}^3            \\
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:interp}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The first equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is a numeric integration on interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[t^n,t^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 with polynomial nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n,1}=t^n,t^{n,2}=t^n+c_2\inc t,t^{n,3}=t^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, which demands: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        b_1 & = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{6{c_2}}     \\
        b_2 & = \frac{1}{6{c_2}(1-{c_2})}          \\
        b_3 & = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{6(1-{c_2})} \\
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:integ}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The Hermite interpolation gives 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 local truncation error 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\inc t^4)$
\end_inset

, and the numeric integration gives 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 local truncation error 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\inc t^3)$
\end_inset

, therefore the classic order of accuracy of HIRK 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is 3. If 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=1/2$
\end_inset

, then the numeric integration 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes a Gauss-Lobatto quadrature rule, which yields a local truncation error of 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\inc t^4)$
\end_inset

, making the scheme 4th order accurate. Also, from the interpolation, no matter the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

, HIRK has a stage order of 3, making it stiffly accurate.
\end_layout

