\begin_layout Standard
HIRK's Butcher tableau in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:HM3Butcher"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 indicates that apart from the first stage, the other two stages seem fully coupled, but following the original formulation of HIRK 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 which originates from interpolation and integration, clearly the internal stage 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 can be explicitly expressed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^n, \uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 with the interpolation relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and one only need to solve 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HM3-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 implicitly. Therefore, the first solving strategy this paper considers is identical to the spirit of NIRK, which solves the equation: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:eqFull}
    \uu^{n+1} -
    \left(\uu^{n} + \inc t
    \left[
        b_1\R(t^{n,1}, \uu^n) +
        b_2\R(t^{n,2}, \uu^*) +
        b_3\R(t^{n,3}, \uu^{n+1})
        \right]
    \right)  =  0
\end{equation}
\end_inset

For simplicity, we denote the residual of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:eqFull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \Res(\uu^{n+1}) \doteq \uu^{n+1} -
    \left(\uu^{n} + \inc t
    \left[
        b_1\R(t^{n,1}, \uu^{n}) +
        b_2\R(t^{n,2}, \uu^{*}) +
        b_3\R(t^{n,3}, \uu^{n+1})
        \right]
    \right)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Considering 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n}$
\end_inset

 is known, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{*}$
\end_inset

 is explicitly expressed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Res(\uu^{n+1})$
\end_inset

 is considered only a function of unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

. The Newton-Raphson method applied to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:eqFull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

's solving would be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \uu^{n+1,m+1}                  & =  \uu^{n+1,m} + \inc \uu^{n+1,m}, \\
        \frac{\partial \Res(\uu^{n+1,m})}
        {\uu^{n+1,m}} \inc \uu^{n+1,m} & = - \Res(\uu^{n+1,m})
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

and adding the pseudo time continuation would be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:ntDtau}
    \begin{aligned}
        \uu^{n+1,m+1}            & =  \uu^{n+1,m} + \inc \uu^{n+1,m}, \\
        \left(
        \frac{\partial \Res(\uu^{n+1,m})}
        {\uu^{n+1,m}} + \inc t \Tau^{-1}
        \right) \inc \uu^{n+1,m} & = - \Res(\uu^{n+1,m})
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Tau=\mathrm{diag}(\tau_1,...\tau_N)$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with local pseudo time steps as its diagonal values. The pseudo time continuation of Newton iteration could be both understood as a relaxation of original method for nonlinear stability, or as the result of solving dual time stepping method Jameson developed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "jameson1991time"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. In other words, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ntDtau"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is the result of solving pseudo time evolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\uu^{n+1}}{d\tau} = -\frac{\Res}{\inc t}$
\end_inset

 with linearly implicit backward Euler method and a local time stepping. Such dual time stepping is prevalent in transient flow solution due to the nonlinearity in fluid systems. However, pseudo time term could cause trouble if we try to solve HIRK of any MIRK type system with certain approaches, which will be illustrated later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expanded form of residual's Jacobian is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:fullJCB}
    \begin{aligned}
        \frac{\partial \Res(\uu^{n+1})}
        {\uu^{n+1}}
                     & = \eye - \inc t b_3 \J^{n+1} -
        \inc t b_2\J^*(a_2\eye +\inc t d_2 \J^{n+1})                                \\
                     & = \frac{d_2 + a_2b_3}{d_2}\eye
        -\frac{a_2b_3}{d_2}\left(
        \eye + \frac{d_2b_2}{b_3}\inc t\J^*
        \right)\left(
        \eye + \frac{d_2}{a_2}\inc t\J^{n+1}
        \right)                                                                     \\
        \text{with:} &                                                              \\
                     & \J^* = \frac{\partial \R(t^{n,2},\uu^*)}{\partial \uu^*},\ \
        \J^{n+1} = \frac{\partial \R(t^{n,3},\uu^{n+1})}{\partial \uu^{n+1}}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

which is a quadratic polynomial of right-hand-sides' Jacobian. If the Jacobian matrices could be explicitly formed and manipulated, solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ntDtau"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 would be straightforward. But a lot of high order methods rely on matrix-free Jacobian evaluation, thus solving the linear system with its matrix in the form of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fullJCB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 would be troublesome or impossible. Even if one would like to use a matrix-less linear solver like Krylov space solvers, powerful matrix-free preconditioners like ILU(0) or LUSGS would be unavailable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to the complexity of Jacobian by Kulikov and Shindin is using an approximate factorization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "kulikov2006familyNIRKOrig,kulikov2009adaptive"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. For the forth order Gauss type NIRK in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "kulikov2006familyNIRKOrig"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Kulikov and Shindin used 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eye-\inc t /4 \J)^2$
\end_inset

 as an approximation. This paper considers the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:factJCB}
    \begin{aligned}
        \frac{\partial \Res(\uu^{n+1})}
        {\uu^{n+1}}
         & \approx
        -\frac{a_2b_3}{d_2}\left(
        \eye + \frac{d_2b_2}{b_3}\inc t\J^*
        \right)\left(
        \eye + \frac{d_2}{a_2}\inc t\J^{n+1}
        \right)    \\
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

which is directly taken from the last term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fullJCB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and the omitted term is identity matrix with coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d_2 + a_2b_3}{d_2}>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

. Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_2<0$
\end_inset

 for any possible 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using a factorized form of approximate Jacobian like 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:factJCB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 enables the use of two successive matrix-free solvers to obtain the increment for Newton iteration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For practical CFD implementation, pseudo time term is now considered. In order to preserve the factorized form, this paper finds using 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:ntDtau_Fact}
