\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 unknown has two major drawbacks. The first drawback is that additional memory would be required for 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

's storage. Considering HIRK saves much space compared to DIRK methods, and HIRK also requires some more space for intermediate results even using explicit 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 evaluation, the first drawback would not be significant. The second drawback is the increase in the dimension of algebraic system. Normally, the enlarged system can be solved using appropriate blocking strategy, for example in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "pazner2017stage"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. However, the current scheme takes a different form of iteration which takes two sub-steps: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:intersolve}
    \begin{aligned}
        \uu^{*,m+1}   & = \uu^{*,m} - \left[
            \eye - \inc t \frac{\partial \Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m})}
            {\partial \uu^{*,m}}
            + \inc t \Tau^{-1}
            \right]
        \backslash \Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m}) \\
        \uu^{n+1,m+1} & = \uu^{n+1,m} - \left[
            \eye - \inc t \frac{\partial \Res^{}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m+1})}
            {\partial \uu^{n+1,m}}
            + \inc t \Tau^{-1}
            \right]
        \backslash \Res^{}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m+1}) \\
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\backslash \mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 notation means to solve the linear problem 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 once. The residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\Res^{*'}$
\end_inset

 is defined with: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1},\uu^{*}) = \Res^*(\uu^{n+1},\uu^{*}) + \beta\Res(\uu^{n+1},\uu^{*})
\end{equation}
\end_inset

which serves as the residual preconditioned with transformation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}
    \begin{bmatrix}
        \Res^{} \\
        \Res^{*'}
    \end{bmatrix} =
    \begin{bmatrix}
        \eye & 0 \\ \beta\eye & \eye
    \end{bmatrix}
    \begin{bmatrix}
        \Res^{} \\
        \Res^{*}
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

. In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "jameson2017evaluation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Jameson used the inverse of Butcher coefficients for preconditioning, which makes off-diagonal blocks of the Jacobian scalar. That preconditioning could be adopted in the current method, but is not recommended for possible instabilities in the presence of negative pressure fixing in numeric tests. ####
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solving procedure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intersolve"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 could be regarded as successively updating 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Res^{*'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Res^{}$
\end_inset

, by using the latest values of the other DOF. Within a linear context, this would be a blocks Gauss-Seidel iteration over the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 blocks of system with each block being 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

. In other words,to solve: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}
    \begin{bmatrix}
        \Res^{}(\uu^{n+1},\uu^{*}) \\
        \Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1},\uu^{*})
    \end{bmatrix} = 0
\end{equation*}
\end_inset

the canonical quasi Newton iteration would need to solve 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:fullCoupled}
    \begin{bmatrix}
        \frac{\partial\Res^{}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m})}{\partial\uu^{n+1,m}} + \inc t\Tau^{-1} &
        \frac{\partial\Res^{}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m})}{\partial\uu^{*,m}}                       \\
        \frac{\partial\Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m})}{\partial\uu^{n+1,m}}                 &
        \frac{\partial\Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m})}{\partial\uu^{*,m}} + \inc t\Tau^{-1}   \\
    \end{bmatrix}
    \begin{bmatrix}
        \inc\uu^{n+1,m} \\
        \inc\uu^{*,m}
    \end{bmatrix}
    =
    -\begin{bmatrix}
        \Res^{}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m}) \\
        \Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1,m},\uu^{*,m})
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

to update both stage values concurrently. The current method 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intersolve"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 first solve the second block row of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fullCoupled"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the increment of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

, then solve the first block row for the increment of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 using updated 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

. The current solving strategy will be referred to as successive solving in the following parts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The omitting of off-diagonal relations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fullCoupled"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, or the block nonlinear Gauss-Seidel handling on the top layer of algorithm brings about extra error in iteration, causing slow-down of iteration and possible divergence. To analyze such behavior, the current research investigates the impact of successive solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intersolve"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 brought to solution of HIRK applied to linear problems using precise linear solvers. With a traditional quasi Newton iteration, if pseudo time steps approaches infinity, the iteration would converge in the first step in such situation. The introduction of successive solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intersolve"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 renders this one-step-convergence impossible, thus the convergence with successive solving will represent all the deceleration effect caused by it. The linear situation discussed could also be a linearization of a non-linear ODE when the stage values converge near the solution, and the instant convergence of Newton iteration would be first order accurate. In the linear or linearized scene, the residual takes the form: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:linearized}
    \begin{aligned}
        \Res^{}(\uu^{n+1},\uu^{*})   & =
        \Res^{}_0 - \inc t b_2\J^*\uu^{*} + (\eye - \inc t b_3\J)\uu^{n+1} \\
        \Res^{*'}(\uu^{n+1},\uu^{*}) & =
        \Res^{*'}_0 + (\eye - \beta\inc t b_2\J^*)\uu^{*}
        + ((\beta-a_2)\eye - \inc t (\beta b_3 - d_2)\J)\uu^{n+1}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\J^*, \J$
\end_inset

 are Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 at the solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{*}, \uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

. Applying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intersolve"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to this linear form and assuming a infinite pseudo time step, following textbook analysis conducted on Gauss-Seidel iteration, the successive solving becomes a linear fixed point iteration, with fixed point mapping's matrix being 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \mathbf{B}_{SS}=\begin{bmatrix}
        \eye - \beta\inc t b_2\J^* & 0                   \\
        - \inc t b_2\J^*           & \eye - \inc t b_3\J \\
    \end{bmatrix}^{-1}
    \begin{bmatrix}
        0 & (\beta-a_2)\eye - \inc t (\beta b_3 - d_2)\J \\
        0 & 0                                            \\
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Thus, convergence of the fixed point iteration equals to the condition 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:rhoGS}
    \begin{aligned}
         & \varUpsilon(\mathbf{B}_{SS}) \\
         & =\varUpsilon\left(
        -[\eye - \inc t b_3\J]^{-1}
        [- \inc t b_2\J^*]
        [\eye - \beta\inc t b_2\J^*]^{-1}
        [(\beta-a_2)\eye - \inc t (\beta b_3 - d_2)\J]
        \right)                         \\
         & < 1
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varUpsilon$
\end_inset

 is spectral radius of matrix. For arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\J,\J^*$
\end_inset

, further analysis is difficult, so we limit the situation to where 
\begin_inset Formula $\J = \J^*$
\end_inset

 is an acceptable approximation, or the ODE is linear itself. Using the Jordan form, and assuming all the inverse are existent and precisely solved, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rhoGS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 would become 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:rhoGS1}
    \begin{aligned}
        \varrho_i =
        \left|
        -[1 -  b_3z_i]^{-1}
        [- b_2z_i]
        [1 - \beta b_2z_i]^{-1}
        [(\beta-a_2) - (\beta b_3 - d_2)z_i]
        \right| & < 1,\ \ \forall z_i = \inc t \lambda_i
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_i$
\end_inset

 is eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\J$
\end_inset

. By further assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{Re} z_i < 0$
\end_inset

 which is true for stable semi-discretized method used on bounded linear problems, special cases were analyzed. For 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=0.5, \beta=0.5$
\end_inset

, it is found 
\begin_inset Formula $\varrho_i < 0.5$
\end_inset

. For 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=0.5, \beta=1$
\end_inset

, it is found 
\begin_inset Formula $\varrho_i < 0.42$
\end_inset

. For 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=0.55, \beta=0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varrho_i$
\end_inset

 could exceed 1. For 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=0.55, \beta=1$
\end_inset

, it is found 
\begin_inset Formula $\varrho_i < 0.36$
\end_inset

. These analyses are trivial which involve finding maximal points in the left complex plane and on the imaginary axis.
\end_layout

